  "title": "Concept of Autopoiesis",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "38febf53ef155616",
      "text": "# Discussion of the Concept of Autopoiesis"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1e9cdb211bc3baeb",
      "text": "LUHMANN, Niklas, 2004. Einführung in die Systemtheorie. 2. Aufl. Heidelberg: Carl-Auer-Verl. Sozialwissenschaften. ISBN 3-89670-459-1, p. 116–118, thinks it is important to preserve the hardness of the term, that is, to say: A system is either autopoietic or non-autopoietic. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a5afd99ab6c85059",
      "text": "It can't be a little bit autopoietic. For with reference to \"autos\" it is clear that the operations of the system are either produced in the system or else predetermined in important respects by the environment, for example by a program according to which a computer operates."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "df6748aee78e38e3",
      "text": "Here an either-or applies. For life this is clear, you are either alive or you are dead. There are only seconds in which doctors can doubt whether one is still alive or already dead. A woman is either pregnant or she is not pregnant, but she cannot be a little bit pregnant. The example comes from Maturana himself, ipsissima verba. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7179f28fd0e79498",
      "text": "This means that the concept of autopoiesis is not a gradualizable concept, and this in turn means that one cannot explain the evolution of complex systems in terms of autopoiesis. If one tries to do so, one arrives at theories which say that a system slowly becomes more autopoietic. Initially, it is still completely dependent on the environment and gradually it gains autonomy, then first of all the structures become more independent of the environment, a little or more or less, and then gradually the system becomes more and more autopoietic in its operations. There is this tendency. Gunther Teubner in Florence has made a corresponding proposal to be able to include evolutionary theoretical considerations in the theory of autopoietic systems. In the meantime, I am also aware of business management literature that gradualizes the autopoiesis or autonomy of operations in a certain way and arrives at a concept such as \"relative autonomy\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b05d3e27f9921a9a",
      "text": "A system is relatively autonomous. It is in some respects independent of the environment, in other respects dependent on the environment. In the strict understanding of the word autopoiesis, however, nothing is said about dependence or independence from the environment. For it is a causal question in which respects a system is dependent on the environment or how the environment affects the system. And this, in turn, is a question that must be posed to an observer of the system."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1ac8afa0215255a3",
      "text": "Furthermore, one cannot assume a principle of sum constancy, according to which a system is the more independent of the environment, the less dependent it is. Numerous experiences indicate that very complex systems which are autonomous to a high degree, if one may qualify the word, increase in independence and in specific dependence at the same time. In modern society, an economic system, a legal system, or a political system is highly independent, but equally dependent on the environment. If the economy does not flourish, it becomes politically difficult, and if politics is not able to provide certain assurances, for example about law, or if politics intervenes too much, this becomes a problem in the economy. We have to distinguish, this leads back to the thesis of operational closure, between causal dependence/independence on the one hand and self-generated operations on the other."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "84a7ea0766c9a863",
      "text": "I am not even so sure myself whether this is ultimately convincing. We have, especially in European culture, a strong notion of converting everything into causality and then, for example, also understanding terms like \"an operation produces an operation\" or \"production\" always causally. This makes it difficult to think of operational closure as completely separate from causal theories. We keep slipping into the idea that the thesis of operational closure is a particular thesis about the internal causality of systems. In a sense, it is. One can convert it to causality. But in principle, the point should be taken to be that the condition of inferentiality is not a condition sufficient to bring about the next state of affairs. This is exactly what the notion of structural coupling deals with, with which I will introduce the next lesson."
    }
