        "id": "38febf53ef155616",
        "text": "# Discussion of the Concept of Autopoiesis"
      },
      "date": 1657791824302
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "1e9cdb211bc3baeb"
      },
      "id": "1e9cdb211bc3baeb",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "38febf53ef155616",
      "date": 1657791895916
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1e9cdb211bc3baeb",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "1e9cdb211bc3baeb",
        "text": "I think it is important to preserve the hardness of the term, that is, to say: A system is either autopoietic or non-autopoietic. It can't be a little bit autopoietic. For with reference to \"autos\" it is clear that the operations of the system are either produced in the system or else predetermined in important respects by the environment, for example by a program according to which a computer operates. Here an either-or applies. For life this is clear, you are either alive or you are dead. There are only seconds in which doctors can doubt whether one is still alive or already dead. A woman is either pregnant or she is not pregnant, but she cannot be a little bit pregnant. The example comes from Maturana himself, ipsissima verba. This means that the concept of autopoiesis is not a gradualizable concept, and this in turn means that one cannot explain the evolution of complex systems in terms of autopoiesis. If one tries to do so, one arrives at theories which say that a system slowly becomes more autopoietic. Initially, it is still completely dependent on the environment and gradually it gains autonomy, then first of all the structures become more independent of the environment, a little or more or less, and then gradually the system becomes more and more autopoietic in its operations. There is this tendency. Gunther Teubner in Florence has made a corresponding proposal to be able to include evolutionary theoretical considerations in the theory of autopoietic systems.40 In the meantime, I am also aware of business management literature that gradualizes the autopoiesis or autonomy of operations in a certain way and arrives at a concept such as \"relative autonomy\"."
      },
